nchanging climate in the Eastern Mediterranean between 1300 and 1100 BC.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This candidate proposes a novel, atypical mechanism: a climate-induced disruption of maritime trade winds, not just drought. It treats the network as a tightly coupled system where the failure of trade routes is as critical as local harvest failure. This is a more speculative but physically plausible conjecture that differentiates it from the standard drought and systems-collapse models.\"}",
